Installing Acrobat reader on Linux:

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

For preferences, see ~/wisdom/setup/setup-preferences

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

Ubuntu:

## This didn't work!
# sudo apt-add-repository "deb http://archive.canonical.com/ubuntu Saucy partner"
# sudo apt update
# sudo apt install acroread

## This didn't work!
# Download .deb from http://get.adobe.com/reader/otherversions/
# Open it (may take a moment).
# I had to look at the "bad quality" details and then "ignore and install".  :-(

http://ubuntuforums.org/showthread.php?t=2181100 says:
1. Download the DEB for Adobe Reader from Adobe website
http://get.adobe.com/uk/reader/
2. Install with following commands
[This is very slow??]
sudo dpkg -i --force-architecture AdbeRdr9.5.5-1_i386linux_enu.deb && sudo apt -f install
To explain this, the switch -i --force-architecture installs 32-bit architecture and -f install installs missing libraries for Kubuntu 13.10 Saucy Salamander 64-bit
3. Repeat the same steps as for Ubuntu plus run following command (installs missing libraries)
sudo apt install libxml2:i386 lib32stdc++6
4. Run Adobe Reader from you terminal first, just type
acroread
5. I got some errors there but after that Adobe Reader is running just fine.

